// _redirects.json — redirect map for originalfreenations.com
//
// Format: JSON5 (https://json5.org) — comments, trailing commas, unquoted keys.
// `from` is a REGEX anchored against the request path; `to` may use $1..$n capture
// groups. `permanent: true` => 301 (default is 302).
//
// This file is the SINGLE SOURCE OF TRUTH. eleventy.config.js parses it at build
// time (so a syntax error fails the build rather than silently shipping no
// redirects), copies it to _site/, and generates _site/xmit.toml from it.
//
// RULES ARE EVALUATED IN ORDER — most specific first.
//
// Derived from the WordPress export (originalfreenations.WordPress.2026-07-08.xml)
// and the SiteSucker crawl of the live site (_raw_archive/originalfreenations.com).
//
// NOT redirected, deliberately:
//   * All 60 post/page slugs — the old site used /%postname%/ and every slug
//     carries over 1:1. Redirecting them would be a no-op at best.
//   * The tag archives — /tag/<slug>/ exists on the new site with the same slugs.
//     The 11 EXCEPTIONS are slugs that were only ever CATEGORIES (they had a tag
//     archive on the new site only while categories were folded into tags); they
//     are redirected to /category/<slug>/ below.
//   * /wp-admin/, /wp-login.php, /xmlrpc.php, /wp-json/* — bot-magnet URLs. Let them
//     404. Redirecting them to / would launder crawl signal onto the homepage.
//   * 77 orphaned WordPress attachment pages (no parent post). A redirect would be a
//     soft-404; an honest 404 is better.
//   * The 56 surviving /wp-content/uploads/ originals — they are served verbatim,
//     so they return 200 and need no rule. Their 166 deleted WordPress size
//     variants ARE mapped below, one explicit rule each.
//
// KNOWN GAP — query-string shortlinks:
//   WordPress always honored /?p=<ID> and /?page_id=<ID>, and 62 such IDs exist
//   (range 23..13174; see the WXR). Those URLs are common in old emails and
//   external links. They are NOT handled here because `from` is matched against the
//   request PATH — a static host has no query string to match on, so no rule in this
//   file can catch them. Fixing it needs either a host-level rule or a small JS
//   shim on the 404 page that reads location.search and forwards. Flagged, not solved.

{
  redirects: [

    // -- Renamed slug ------------------------------------------------------
    // The only _wp_old_slug in the entire export. WordPress served this as a
    // redirect, so it is a live URL in the wild.
    { from: '^/1358-2/?$', to: '/tecumsehs-speech/', permanent: true },

    // -- Feeds -------------------------------------------------------------
    // The old site had 117 feed URLs (root + per category/tag/author). The new
    // site has one. /feed/ is the single highest-value redirect here: every RSS
    // subscriber and aggregator points at it.
    { from: '^/feed/?$', to: '/feed/feed.rss', permanent: true },
    { from: '^/(?:category|tag|author)/[^/]+/feed/?$', to: '/feed/feed.rss', permanent: true },

    // -- Categories ----------------------------------------------------------
    // /category/<x>/ IS A REAL PAGE NOW. `categories` and `tags` are two separate
    // taxonomies (built in one pass in eleventy.config.js); src/categories.njk
    // writes an archive for each of the 12 public categories. Counts match the
    // export exactly: doctrine-of-discovery 9, religion 7, biblical 6, politics 6,
    // news 5, culture 5, legal 4, history 2, archive 2, american-dream 1,
    // corona-virus 1, tecumseh-shawnee-leader 1.
    //
    // So there is NO rule mapping those 12 slugs anywhere, and there is NO
    // catch-all on /category/. Both used to exist and both are gone on purpose:
    //
    //   * `/category/(american-dream|…)/ -> /tag/$1/` — it pointed at the tag
    //     archives the old category-folding produced. Those are gone; the category
    //     archive is the destination now, and it is served directly.
    //
    //   * `^/category/[^/]+(?:/page/\d+)?/?$ -> /news/` — a catch-all that would
    //     also match all 12 REAL category URLs. Whether a redirect can shadow an
    //     existing file is host behavior we cannot verify from here (xmit documents
    //     the TOML format, not the precedence), so the rule is not left in place on
    //     the hope that "static file wins". A negative lookahead excluding the 12
    //     slugs would also be a gamble: several regex engines (Go/RE2 among them)
    //     have no lookahead at all. Enumerating instead is safe under EVERY
    //     precedence rule and EVERY engine.
    //
    // Only the categories with NO archive are redirected, plus pagination:
    //
    //   uncategorized — WordPress's default term was RENAMED to "federal Indian
    //     law" but KEPT the slug `uncategorized`, and it carries 42 of 57 posts.
    //     The converter never wrote it into front matter, so it is not a category
    //     here (nor should it be — it is not a real topic). Goes to /news/.
    //
    //   featured — an INTERNAL term, excluded from BOTH taxonomies, so neither
    //     /category/featured/ nor /tag/featured/ is ever built. Goes to /news/.
    //
    // WordPress had exactly these 14 category slugs, so nothing else is reachable;
    // an unknown /category/<junk>/ now 404s honestly, like every other junk URL.
    { from: '^/category/uncategorized(?:/page/\\d+)?/?$', to: '/news/', permanent: true },
    { from: '^/category/featured(?:/page/\\d+)?/?$', to: '/news/', permanent: true },
    // Old WordPress category pagination. The new archives are single-page, so
    // /page/N/ collapses onto the archive itself.
    { from: '^/category/(american-dream|archive|biblical|corona-virus|culture|doctrine-of-discovery|history|legal|news|politics|religion|tecumseh-shawnee-leader)/page/\\d+/?$', to: '/category/$1/', permanent: true },

    // -- Unfolded tags --> categories ----------------------------------------
    // These 11 slugs used to have a /tag/<x>/ archive ONLY because categories were
    // folded into tags. They are categories, not tags: no post carries them as a
    // tag, so /tag/<x>/ is no longer built and would 404. Send each to its category
    // archive, which holds exactly the same posts.
    //
    // `american-dream` is the ONE name that is BOTH a category and a real tag, so
    // /tag/american-dream/ IS still built (1 post) and MUST NOT be redirected.
    // `featured` is internal and never had a /tag/ page. Everything else below the
    // /feed/ rule above, so /tag/<x>/feed/ still goes to the feed.
    { from: '^/tag/(archive|biblical|corona-virus|culture|doctrine-of-discovery|history|legal|news|politics|religion|tecumseh-shawnee-leader)/?$', to: '/category/$1/', permanent: true },

    // -- Authors -------------------------------------------------------------
    // WordPress used the login in the URL; the new site uses a real slug.
    // /author/haleiwa/ is Steven Newcomb and is the one that matters (55 posts).
    // /author/dave/ never had published content but still resolved with a 200.
    // New author pages do not paginate, so /page/N/ collapses to the archive.
    { from: '^/author/haleiwa(?:/page/\\d+)?/?$', to: '/author/steven-newcomb/', permanent: true },
    { from: '^/author/adamdjbrett(?:/page/\\d+)?/?$', to: '/author/adam-brett/', permanent: true },
    { from: '^/author/dave(?:/page/\\d+)?/?$', to: '/author/david-ratcliffe/', permanent: true },

    // -- Root pagination -----------------------------------------------------
    // Old /page/2..5/ were the homepage archive. The new site paginates at
    // /latest/page/N/, so the shape is preserved and deep links stay meaningful.
    { from: '^/page/(\\d+)/?$', to: '/latest/page/$1/', permanent: true },

    // -- Attachment pages ----------------------------------------------------
    // WordPress published a page per uploaded file. These 82 had a parent post,
    // so they redirect to the post the image belonged to — which is what someone
    // following such a link actually wanted. (The 77 orphans are left to 404.)
