    // -- Media: /wp-content/uploads/ size variants ---------------------------
    // WordPress generated a -WIDTHxHEIGHT (and -scaled) derivative for every
    // upload. Those 166 derivatives were DELETED — they were pure duplicates of
    // an original that is still served — and each old URL is 301'd here to the
    // full-resolution file that survives. 56 originals remain, served VERBATIM
    // from src/public/wp-content/uploads/, so they still return 200 with
    // byte-identical content. That took uploads/ from 28MB to ~13MB.
    //
    // The site's own pages do NOT use these files at all — they serve
    // /assets/images/*.webp. This tree exists purely for legacy inbound links.
    //
    // Rules are EXPLICIT AND LITERAL, one per deleted file, on purpose. A
    // generic "strip -WxH" regex is WRONG here: 9 of the SURVIVING originals
    // themselves end in -WxH or -scaled (no un-suffixed original was ever
    // exported), so a generic rule would redirect a live file to a 404, and
    // 33 of the deleted files map to a -scaled keeper rather than a bare name.
    //
    // Two deliberate exceptions to "redirect to the largest file":
    //   * Marshalls-laptop-1: the 5312x2988 original is stored ROTATED with no
    //     EXIF orientation tag, so it renders sideways. Its variants point at
    //     -1024x576.jpg (upright) instead, which is kept for that reason.
    //   * The Eventbrite thumbnail: its only full-size original is .avif, so the
    //     .jpg variants point at -900x450.jpg (kept) to preserve content-type.

